A botnet is a network of devices secretly infected with malware and controlled by someone else. These “zombie” devices can send spam, overload servers (DDoS), or spread more malware—often without users knowing. Infection happens through fake apps, unsafe downloads, or system flaws. Once connected to the internet, compromised devices quietly receive commands. Firewalls, updates, and isolation reduce risk, but once inside a network, a botnet can move fast. Terms like command-and-control (C2), rootkit, persistence, and lateral movement help explore how attackers maintain access and why complete separation of systems can break the chain.